" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "Do the rest from 1
 to 10.   " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 31 "Note:  it is possible to us
e a " }{TEXT 263 9 "for loop " }{TEXT -1 69 " to simplify this task si
nce we are doing a repetitive calculation.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 29 "Note:  Also, the the command " }{TEXT 265 6 "coeffs" }{TEXT -1 
15 " unfortunately " }{TEXT 266 8 "does not" }{TEXT -1 36 " pick off t
he coefficients in order." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "The " }{TEXT 259 16 "Binomial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 
66 " gives a formula for finding the coefficients of the expansion of \+
" }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)^n;" "6#),&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&%\"nG" }{TEXT -1 
10 "  for any " }{TEXT 267 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 ".  It is relatively obv
ious that the coefficient of  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "a^(n-k)*b^k;" "6#*&)%
\"aG,&%\"nG\"\"\"%\"kG!\"\"F()%\"bGF)F(" }{TEXT -1 19 "  for any value
 of " }{TEXT 268 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 11 " from 0 to " }{TEXT 269 1 "n" }
{TEXT -1 46 " is given by the number of ways we can choose " }{TEXT 
270 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 8 " of the " }{TEXT 294 1 "b" }{TEXT -1 12 "'s fro
m the " }{TEXT 271 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 295 1 "b" }{TEXT -1 
20 "'s in the expansion " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)*(a+b)" "6#*&,&%\"aG\"
\"\"%\"bGF&F&,&F%F&F'F&F&" }{TEXT -1 7 " ....( " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)
" "6#,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF%" }{TEXT -1 5 " ),  " }{TEXT 272 1 "n" }
{TEXT -1 41 " times .   The number of combinations of " }{TEXT 273 1 "
n" }{TEXT -1 18 " objects choosing " }{TEXT 274 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 12 " a
t a time, " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "nCk" "6#%$nCkG" }{TEXT -1 27 ", is given b
y the formula  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "nCk=n!/(k!*(n-k)!)" "6#/%$nCkG*&-%*fa
ctorialG6#%\"nG\"\"\"*&-F'6#%\"kGF*-F'6#,&F)F*F.!\"\"F*F2" }{TEXT -1 
2 " ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 261 10 
"State the " }{TEXT 260 16 "Binomial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 
275 31 "and use Maple to demonstrate it" }{TEXT -1 1 "." }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "Every binomial has  coefficients from the expansion
 of (a+b)^n for any n.  These coefficients can be expressed with Pasca
l's Triangle solved by finding the expansion of (a+b)^n for any n and \+
then taking the coefficients from the expanded statements." }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 111 "proof ;  the equation below is an  expan
sion using b=1, the coefficients are 14641 taken from Pascal's triangl
e" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "expand((a+1)^4);" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,,*$)%\"aG\"\"%\"\"\"F(*&F'F()F&\"\"$F
(F(*&\"\"'F()F&\"\"#F(F(*&F'F(F&F(F(F(F(" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 8 "Compute " }{XPPEDIT 
18 0 "sum(binomial(n,k),k=0..n)" "6#-%$sumG6$-%)binomialG6$%\"nG%\"kG/
F*;\"\"!F)" }{TEXT -1 34 "  for n=1 to 10.  Here the symbol " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "Sigma;" "6#%&SigmaG" }{TEXT -1 70 " (Greek letter Sigma
) stands for sum.   (See the worksheet SumSeq.mws)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 78 "for n from 1
 to 10 do Sum(binomial(n,k),k=0..n)=sum(binomial(n,k),k=0..n); od;" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#/-%$SumG6$-%)binomialG6$\"\"\"%\"kG/F+
;\"\"!F*\"\"#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#/-%$SumG6$-%)binomial
G6$\"\"#%\"kG/F+;\"\"!F*\"\"%" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#/-%$S
umG6$-%)binomialG6$\"\"$%\"kG/F+;\"\"!F*\"\")" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#/-%$SumG6$-%)binomialG6$\"\"%%\"kG/F+;\"\"!F*\"#;" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#/-%$SumG6$-%)binomialG6$\"\"&%\"kG/F+;
\"\"!F*\"#K" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#/-%$SumG6$-%)binomialG6
$\"\"'%\"kG/F+;\"\"!F*\"#k" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#/-%$SumG
6$-%)binomialG6$\"\"(%\"kG/F+;\"\"!F*\"$G\"" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#/-%$SumG6$-%)binomialG6$\"\")%\"kG/F+;\"\"!F*\"$c#" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#/-%$SumG6$-%)binomialG6$\"\"*%\"kG/F+;
\"\"!F*\"$7&" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#/-%$SumG6$-%)binomialG
6$\"#5%\"kG/F+;\"\"!F*\"%C5" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "
> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 
"" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 258 63 "What general formula do the above \+
calculations in  suggest? 2^n" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 388 "2.  Pascal's Triangle.  Recall the defin
ition of Pascal's Triangle.   Use Maple to construct the first 10 rows
 of Pascal's Triangle. (The trick will be to get the coefficients to o
ccur in the correct order.  The Maple command for generating a sequenc
e might be helpful. It is   seq(expression(i),i=m..n);   where express
ion(i) is an expression with index i and m..n is a range of numbers." 
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 3 "   " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 57 "for n from 0 to 10 do seq(coeff((a+1)^n,a,i),i=0..n);
 od;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"\"\"" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"\"F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6%\"\"\"\"\"#
F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6&\"\"\"\"\"$F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 
1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6'\"\"\"\"\"%\"\"'F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 
20 "6(\"\"\"\"\"&\"#5F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6)\"\"\"
\"\"'\"#:\"#?F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6*\"\"\"\"\"(\"#@
\"#NF&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6+\"\"\"\"\")\"#G\"#c\"#
qF&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6,\"\"\"\"\"*\"#O\"#%)\"$E
\"F'F&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6-\"\"\"\"#5\"#X\"$?\"\"
$5#\"$_#F'F&F%F$F#" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 214 "3.  Functions.  In this exerci
se we study the basic properties of polynomials and rational functions
.  Some revelant MAPLE commands will be   factor, expand, solve, fsolv
e, denom, numer, simplify, subs,   ....... ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 171 "     The first thing we need to learn is how to define a funct
ion.  There are two ways, each with its own advantages and disadvantag
es.  First define the polynomial p1 as " }{TEXT 282 2 "a " }{TEXT -1 
1 "s" }{TEXT 283 23 "ymbolic expression in x" }{TEXT -1 119 " in the f
ollowing way:    p1:=x^2-1;  (Note the colon before the =, this is alw
ays required when defining something.)  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "p1:=x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p1G,
&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F*F*!\"\"" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 39 "     Now define the same polynomial as " 
}{TEXT 281 30 "an operation on the variable x" }{TEXT -1 40 " in the f
ollowing way:     p2:=x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "p2:=x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p2Gf*6#%
\"xG6\"6$%)operatorG%&arrowGF(,&*$)9$\"\"#\"\"\"F1F1!\"\"F(F(F(" }}}
{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 257 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 190 "Try \+
the following command sequences to see some of the differences in how \+
MAPLE  treats these two definitions.  As always record your observatio
ns and comments on the worksheet in text mode." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "p1;" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F(F(!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "p2;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 
"6#%#p2G" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 6 "p2(x);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)%\"xG\"
